# splitter.user-md -- project rules for the splitter top-level tool (Berreman)

This is the Berreman project prompt piece that pairs with the
cross-repo `splitter.system-md`. The splitter passes both paths
to each spawn (splitter / verifier / claim-checker / reconciler);
each spawn reads this file *second* (after the system prompt) for
project-specific rules.

The splitter top-level tool drives the pre-loop split / verify /
claim-check / reconcile rounds; the arc-runner consumes the
manifest the splitter produces. Build / test / code-style rules
that apply to the resulting slices live in
`arc-runner.user-md` -- read that file when the splicing rubric
needs to weigh slice realism against the build tool, the gates,
or the code style.

---

## Defer for build / test / style rules

For everything that is "how an implementation slice runs" --
build commands, gate expectations, `dotnet build` / `dotnet test`,
code style, artifacts-folder discipline, file-naming convention
-- read:

- `./.user-md/Berreman/arc-runner.user-md`

That file is the single source of truth. Do not duplicate any of
its content here.

---

## Slicing rubric pointers

When evaluating a candidate slicing for Berreman arcs, consider:

- The project keeps work slices session-sized -- typically 3-8
  per big spec, rarely more. A 1:1 match with the spec's own
  internal "logical pieces" is a smell that the spec
  under-decomposed; lean toward more slices.
- Berreman's build is fast (a clean `dotnet build` + the
  `BerremanTests` suite usually completes in a few minutes), so
  the default `worker_timeout_sec` is comfortable. Bump it only
  when a slice touches the analytics path or pulls in heavy
  numerical regression tests.
- Slices that change the matrix / eigenvector / Fourier core
  (under `Berreman/Berreman/`) should land before slices that
  touch the runner (`BerremanRunner`) or the model generator
  (`BerremanModelGenerator`), so the dependent code can be
  re-run against the new core in the same arc.
- The project is pure F# numerical code -- no UI, no Android,
  no A/V harness. Slices that would introduce one of those
  capabilities are scope-expanding and deserve operator review
  before the splitter signs off.

---

## HITL gates

The splitter top-level tool runs autonomously between rounds; the
operator's only HITL points are the three sentinel files
`.pause`, `.pending-force`, and `additional-comments.md`, and
editing pending task files in place before the next spawn fires.
There is no project-specific HITL gate beyond what
`splitter.system-md` documents.
